# Cogeto inbound Haraka — receive-only, minimal plugin set (decision 0028).
# Order matters: connection limits first, then sender authentication, then
# recipient validation, then the delivery-to-app queue hook. NO outbound/relay
# plugins are loaded — this server never sends (ruling 4).
#
# STARTTLS: the `tls` plugin is NOT listed here — the entrypoint appends it at
# start ONLY when an instance certificate is mounted (GAP-2), so a cert-less dev
# box still boots while a provisioned instance advertises + accepts STARTTLS.

# Per-remote-host connection concurrency limit (config/cogeto_connlimit.ini) —
# anti-abuse hygiene (ruling 6; GAP-1). A small IN-PROCESS limiter: the bundled
# haraka-plugin-limit needs a Redis backend and crashes init without one, so we
# do not use it. The real throttle on the expensive path is the app-side
# per-sender intake rate cap (SEC-2).
cogeto_connlimit

# Sender authentication (SEC-1): evaluate SPF for the envelope sender and write
# the standard Received-SPF header. cogeto_deliver forwards the verdict to the
# app, which treats only `pass` as authenticated and refuses a hard `fail`.
spf

# Accept mail ONLY for the instance's configured inbound address; refuse every
# other recipient at RCPT (SMTP 550) — recipient validation (ruling 6).
cogeto_rcpt

# The delivery-to-app plugin: at queue time, POST the full raw message to the
# internal authenticated intake endpoint and translate its HTTP verdict into the
# SMTP response (ruling 7). This is the ONLY egress from the mail service, and it
# is an internal HTTP call, not a shared filesystem.
cogeto_deliver
